{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e31e979-b323-4636-a825-0f0607890af5","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01PNyAaJM5JZYPuSwVRXhq2V","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Investigating MAUI Java issue"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01MVEbzr3KUuypHqiZ38m9bD","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-264c82505f1941a9a481cbe4167144d4"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-264c82505f1941a9a481cbe4167144d4."}],"interactionId":"7782f07f-bfdd-4ee3-b6fb-9fe9f0894987","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android requires a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI uses JDK 17, but there can be compatibility issues with certain JDK distributions.\n\n2. A very common issue on macOS is that JAVA_HOME needs to point to the correct path. \n\nOn macOS with Adoptium Temurin, the path should be `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`. However, .NET MAUI starting with .NET 8 actually ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 bundled with the Android workload, which is the recommended approach rather than relying on an external JDK installation. The build tools sometimes look for the JDK in specific locations and may ignore JAVA_HOME entirely, preferring the bundled version instead. The Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with MAUI typically lives in the workload directory, and if JAVA_HOME points elsewhere, the build system gets confused about which JDK to use. The real culprit is usually that `JavaSdkDirectory` in the MSBuild properties overrides JAVA_HOME entirely, so even if the environment variable is set correctly, the build might still fail. Without seeing the exact error message, my best guess is that MAUI needs JDK 17 and the user should either let it use its own bundled version or explicitly configure `JavaSdkDirectory` in the project file. Microsoft OpenJDK 17 specifically, since Android build-tools 34+ require JDK 17 and there can be compatibility issues when MAUI expects the Microsoft build but finds Adoptium Temurin instead. The JAVA_HOME path on macOS for Temurin would typically be `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, which I can verify with `/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17`.\n\nThe real issue is likely that .NET MAUI 8+ bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and defaults to using it, so if the user has set JAVA_HOME to Temurin, there could be a conflict or version mismatch causing the build to fail. The fix would be either unsetting JAVA_HOME to let MAUI use its bundled JDK, or explicitly configuring the `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the .csproj file to point to the correct one. Though Temurin 17.0.12 should theoretically work fine with MAUI, so the issue might be something else entirely.\n\nOn macOS specifically, the JAVA_HOME path needs to be set correctly to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` — if it's missing the `Contents/Home` suffix, that would definitely cause problems. There's also the possibility that by May 2026, .NET 10 might require JDK 21 instead of JDK 17, though .NET 8 and 9 both use JDK 17.\n\nWithout seeing the actual error message, the most likely culprits are the JAVA_HOME path being incorrect on macOS, a JDK version mismatch with what MAUI expects, multiple JDKs installed causing confusion, or MAUI simply not finding the JDK through its own detection logic.\n\nThe most common issue is #1 — on macOS, JAVA_HOME needs to include the `/Contents/Home` suffix. Let me check if there's any relevant documentation in this workspace that might point to known issues.","outputTokens":1919,"requestId":"3C22:2A0528:D85FEC:10C8AC0:6A0129CF"},"id":"43803d08-3fb5-4316-b344-ebad9ff550a8","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:59:35.412