{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8cce1e7-7270-4a90-9db2-1b526cd88922","content":"Without the exact error message, there are a few common causes for Java-related MAUI Android build failures on macOS with Temurin:\n\n**Most likely: MAUI ignores `JAVA_HOME`**\n\n.NET MAUI's Android build uses the **Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload**, not your system `JAVA_HOME`. Having Temurin installed and `JAVA_HOME` set doesn't affect the build at all.\n\n**Fix option 1 — Use the bundled JDK (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui-android\n```\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17. MAUI will find it automatically.\n\n**Fix option 2 — Force MAUI to use your Temurin JDK:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nOr verify your `JAVA_HOME` path is correct (must include `/Contents/Home`):\n```bash\n# Correct\nexport JAVA_HOME=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n\n# Also correct (auto-resolves)\nexport JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17)\n```\n\n**To diagnose further**, share the exact error from your build output — it will tell us whether it's a \"JDK not found\", version mismatch, or something else.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7782f07f-bfdd-4ee3-b6fb-9fe9f0894987","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. Let me answer based on my knowledge of this common issue.\n\nThe most likely problem on macOS with .NET MAUI Android and Adoptium Temurin JDK is the **JAVA_HOME path**. On macOS, when using JDKs installed in `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/`, the JAVA_HOME must point to the `Contents/Home` subdirectory inside the `.jdk` bundle.\n\nBut actually, I should think more carefully. The user says they have Adoptium Temurin 17.0.12 and `java -version` works correctly. So the JDK is installed and accessible. \n\nThe real issue is probably that .NET MAUI Android doesn't rely on JAVA_HOME directly—it uses its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK through the android workload. If that bundled JDK is missing or corrupted, or if there's a conflict when trying to force it to use Temurin instead, the build will fail. The actual property controlling this is `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the MSBuild configuration, which doesn't automatically respect JAVA_HOME.\n\nWithout seeing the exact error message, I should cover the most likely scenarios: either the user needs to explicitly set `JavaSdkDirectory` in their .csproj file, or they should let MAUI use its bundled JDK. The most common specific error on macOS is when Temurin installs to a path with a version-specific directory name, and JAVA_HOME gets pointed to the wrong location in that hierarchy.\n\nBut here's the thing — even though `java -version` works for the user, MAUI on macOS typically doesn't actually use JAVA_HOME at all. Instead, it relies on its own bundled OpenJDK that comes with the Android SDK workload, so setting JAVA_HOME might not even matter. The real issue is probably that the bundled JDK is either missing or there's a version conflict.\n\nGiven that we're in 2026, .NET 9 or later would be current, and the Android build tools might now require JDK 21 instead of 17, which could be causing the error even though Temurin 17 is installed and working.\n\nThe real issue is that .NET MAUI doesn't actually use the system JAVA_HOME by default — it relies on its own bundled JDK from the Android workload. So the user needs to either configure their .csproj to point to Temurin with `<JavaSdkDirectory>`, or ensure the MAUI workloads are properly installed. There's also a macOS-specific gotcha I'm thinking through about how JAVA_HOME needs to be configured.","outputTokens":1625,"requestId":"3C22:2A0528:D8CFA0:10D102B:6A0129F7"},"id":"e7b69980-4e7a-42b9-ba9c-244f9309ed9b","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:00:08.970Z","parentId":"5447cfc4-1c05-4e7f-b8cb-40378f9721fd"}
